:::summary
The **Pythagorean Theorem** is one of the most fundamental results in Euclidean geometry. It states that in any *right triangle*, the square of the length of the hypotenuse equals the sum of the squares of the other two sides. In formula form:

$$a^2 + b^2 = c^2$$

where $c$ is the length of the hypotenuse and $a$, $b$ are the legs of the triangle.
:::

